WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:18.840
Now if you think about how security controls need to be preventive, detective, and corrective,

00:18.840 --> 00:33.720
we've been talking about how...

00:33.720 --> 00:38.920
Now if you think about how security controls need to be preventive, detective, and corrective,

00:38.920 --> 00:46.400
we've been talking about how detective capabilities are provided through IDS and IPS systems.

00:46.400 --> 00:52.720
Now the corrective action that needs to happen after we detect that something is wrong or

00:52.720 --> 00:56.240
against the rules is what this section deals with.

00:56.240 --> 01:01.440
So for example, one of the very first things that we can do is activate sandboxes, and I

01:01.440 --> 01:08.160
know that we've talked about sandboxes before, but a sandbox is like a safe play area.

01:08.160 --> 01:13.960
It's an environment where we can test things, for example, and be able to determine if something

01:13.960 --> 01:18.200
is malicious or not, and that's what we call a sandbox environment.

01:18.200 --> 01:24.840
So one of the things that your IDS, IPS technologies can correct and activate the corrective action

01:24.840 --> 01:31.200
would be to test something in a sandbox environment, and we can determine whether something is either

01:31.200 --> 01:36.200
malicious or not or safe to run in our production environment.

01:36.200 --> 01:41.680
Now when we talk about IDS as an IPS, I think we've talked about this before, however, it's

01:41.680 --> 01:46.760
really important to understand the result that may be returned.

01:46.760 --> 01:53.280
And there are questions on the exam that address this, but basically a IDS slash IPS system

01:53.280 --> 01:58.920
can return what are called false positives and false negatives.

01:58.920 --> 02:04.600
Now don't confuse these with what we talked about in the biometric section, which were

02:04.600 --> 02:09.400
type 1s and type 2s, false rejects and false accepts.

02:09.400 --> 02:11.640
That's not what we're talking about here.

02:11.640 --> 02:17.240
Here the terminology is different, false positives and false negatives.

02:17.240 --> 02:24.560
A false positive is where the IDS system tells us that it is an attack, but in fact it is

02:24.560 --> 02:25.560
not.

02:25.560 --> 02:32.160
And that would actually require the organization to launch into its incident response capability

02:32.160 --> 02:37.960
and at some point determine that it's not a real attack, but we've had to launch into

02:38.000 --> 02:40.360
our incident management capability.

02:40.360 --> 02:46.360
That's a false positive where the IDS system thinks it's an attack, but really isn't.

02:46.360 --> 02:52.760
What's much more critical is what we call a false negative.

02:52.760 --> 02:58.480
This is where the IDS IPS system does not catch something that it should.

02:58.480 --> 03:02.800
And from an organization's perspective, that's much more critical because we should be

03:02.880 --> 03:09.880
catching something that is an issue or an incident, but the IDS IPS system was not able

03:09.880 --> 03:11.120
to do it.

03:11.120 --> 03:18.120
And we've talked about how it's important to fine tune your IDS IPS capabilities so that

03:18.120 --> 03:26.320
we lower, for example, the false positives, but we also try and raise the false negatives.

03:26.800 --> 03:33.800
I mean, we want the IDS IPS system to be as valuable as possible so that it catches everything.

03:33.800 --> 03:40.800
And that requires constant fine tuning so that it returns better decisions on an ongoing

03:40.800 --> 03:42.160
basis.

03:42.160 --> 03:47.280
Now one of the other corrective things that can happen is what a lot of companies have

03:47.280 --> 03:50.680
been focusing on for the last number of years.

03:50.680 --> 03:55.400
And that is to have what are called honeypots and honey nets.

03:55.400 --> 04:01.080
And if you know anything about these, these are fake environments that companies create

04:01.080 --> 04:07.200
to look very attractive so that if an intruder has intruded into your network, you lure

04:07.200 --> 04:11.440
them into these fake environments because they look attractive.

04:11.440 --> 04:17.160
But because they are fake, they can lure these people into those environments so that you

04:17.160 --> 04:19.800
can protect your real environments.

04:19.800 --> 04:23.520
That's the whole purpose of these is to protect your real environments because you're

04:23.520 --> 04:30.440
luring them into fake environments and at the same time, potentially capturing evidence

04:30.440 --> 04:31.960
against the perpetrators.

04:31.960 --> 04:40.480
Now the only difference between honeypot and honeynet is a collection of honeypots.

04:40.480 --> 04:46.080
And what's really important to understand is the legality of these.

04:46.080 --> 04:52.720
Depending on where you put them, they can either be an example of enticement or entrapment.

04:52.720 --> 05:00.120
But the bottom line is companies can use these if someone has already committed a crime.

05:00.120 --> 05:06.480
Someone has already intruded into your network, then we can lure them into these fake environments

05:06.480 --> 05:11.560
and that would be considered to be enticement as opposed to entrapment.

05:11.560 --> 05:15.160
So where you place them is really important part.

05:15.160 --> 05:19.680
And that's what we're trying to highlight here in this very simple network diagram.

05:19.680 --> 05:24.480
The honey nets and the honeypots need to be placed in the right environments so that you

05:24.480 --> 05:30.960
are not entraping individuals but rather enticing them into these fake environments because

05:30.960 --> 05:34.960
they've already done something that is illegal.

05:34.960 --> 05:42.080
And as a final slide here in this section, we need to understand the difference between

05:42.080 --> 05:45.720
enticement and entrapment from a legal perspective.

05:45.720 --> 05:51.640
And this is why we understand that enticement is legal because someone has already committed

05:51.640 --> 05:57.920
a crime and therefore honey nets and honeypots become examples of enticement.

05:57.920 --> 06:04.960
Whereas entrapment would not be legal because you are inducing someone to commit a crime

06:04.960 --> 06:08.280
that they weren't contemplating doing in the first place.

06:08.280 --> 06:13.240
So because they've intruded into your network and then you lure them into your honeypot,

06:13.240 --> 06:17.480
for example, that is an example of enticement.

